      "role": "user",
      "content": "ok thanks. if i go with the lab route, what should i be looking for in the results? like are there specific numbers for blueberries that i need to hit to keep them healthy? also is there anything else that happens underground that might mess with the nutrients besides just chemical levels?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "When reviewing your lab results, look closely at the pH range, as blueberries typically thrive in acidic soil, usually between 4.5 and 5.5. Beyond the chemical levels, you should also look for signs of root health, as compromised roots can prevent even adequate nutrients from being absorbed. Poor drainage, compacted soil, or root rot caused by overwatering can mimic nutrient deficiencies from the surface. These underground conditions are just as important as the chemical readings for blueberry health.",
      "source": "target",
